Badges Applied For: Available, Reusable

=== Justification for "Available" ===

This artifact has been deposited on Zenodo with a permanent DOI (to be provided upon acceptance).
All source code, evaluation scripts, and experimental results are publicly accessible under the
CC-BY-4.0 license. The artifact includes the complete MGO (Multi-Granularity Ordering) dataset
of 58 real-world ordering-related concurrency bugs, along with automated evaluation pipelines
for four verification tools (CBMC, GenMC, Nidhugg, IRhunter).

A pre-built Docker image containing all three primary tools (CBMC, GenMC, Nidhugg) is
available on Docker Hub at `wangshaohao/mgo-ae:latest`, enabling reviewers to reproduce
all results with a single `docker pull` command. No per-tool installation is required.

=== Justification for "Reusable" ===

The artifact is carefully structured and documented to facilitate reuse and repurposing:

1. Well-organized taxonomy: 58 bug samples are hierarchically categorized across three
   abstraction layers (Micro-Instruction Level, Resource Lifecycle Level, Semantic Logic Level),
   with clear labeling including bug ID, source provenance, target system, bug type, and dates.

2. Pre-built Docker image on Docker Hub: Reviewers can pull the complete toolchain via
   `docker pull wangshaohao/mgo-ae:latest`. The image includes CBMC 5.12, GenMC v0.9,
   and Nidhugg 0.4, all compiled and configured for immediate use. A Dockerfile and
   full source code (genmc-src/, nidhugg-src/) are also included for building from source.

3. Automated evaluation scripts: Each tool directory includes ready-to-run shell scripts
   that batch-execute experiments and produce structured CSV summary reports. All scripts
   run inside the Docker container for consistent, reproducible results.

4. Verified results: Pre-computed CSV summary reports are included for cross-validation.
   All results have been verified to be consistent between the host environment,
   the locally-built Docker image, and the Docker Hub image, ensuring that reviewers
   can reproduce the findings regardless of their setup.

5. Containerized environment: All three primary tools (CBMC, GenMC, Nidhugg) run inside
   a single Docker image, eliminating installation friction. IRhunter uses a separate
   Docker image (4ndychin/llvm-ufo) provided by its authors for the UFO instrumentation
   engine.

6. Extensibility: The dataset is tool-agnostic. New verification tools can be applied to
   the same bug samples by following the documented evaluation pattern. The three-layer
   taxonomy provides a clear framework for comparative studies.

7. Detailed documentation: Step-by-step reproduction instructions are provided for each
   tool, including expected outputs, interpretation guidelines for CSV reports, and
   troubleshooting notes for known edge cases.
